<!-- Section 3: The Compounding Effect -->
<section class="bg-white py-16 sm:py-20">
  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6">
    <p class="text-otp-500 text-sm font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest mb-4">The compounding effect</p>
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-extrabold text-gray-900 mb-8 leading-tight">Every agent inherits everything the last agent learned.</h2>

    <div class="space-y-4 text-lg text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">
      <p>Human onboarding starts from scratch every time. You hire someone new. They spend weeks absorbing context. They make mistakes the last person already made. They discover the same failure modes. The learning curve resets.</p>
      <p>Agent onboarding with an OOS is different. <strong class="text-gray-900">The OOS gets better with every failure, every fix, every update.</strong> When Agent #3 hits a coordination problem and you solve it, Agent #4 inherits that solution on day one.</p>
      <p>Every failure mode you document becomes a guardrail. Every escalation path you refine becomes faster. Every coordination pattern you add becomes smoother. The onboarding packet compounds.</p>
      <p class="text-gray-900 font-semibold">Agent #10 starts stronger than Agent #1 ever was -- because it inherits the full operational history of every agent that came before it.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-10 grid sm:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
